Con/text
In the last exhibition organized at 503 Broadway, pho-
tographer and painter Sandra Payne presented a series
unlike those she had previously shown at the gallery (see
Chronology, p. 103). In dozens of works consisting of ink
on peach or lavender paper, she pictured monochro-
matic-black femme figures silhouetted against empty.
grounds. Fleshy, oozing, and at times monstrous, some
looked more vegetal or microbial than human, while
others were abstracted to the point of resembling land-
scapes or ink spills. Payne depicted all members of her
bevy in side view, none matching the "lady's" patrician
profile clocked by the exhibition's title.
In her path-making essay "Olympia's Maid," Lorraine
O'Grady described these works as "joyously sexual and
sublimely spiritual." But, as she recalls, the JAM crowd
was not quite ready for this kind of depiction of Black
femmehood: "The opening reception was one of those
where people speak of everything but what is on the
walls. We do not yet have the courage to look."* Payne
had long been after precisely this kind of fierce encoun-
ter, first introducing herself to Linda Goode Bryant in the
early 1980s in a letter asking for both representation and
a job. "I am interested in remembering the unseen, the
untouched, the unexpected," she wrote in prose that
continues to resonate."-TJL

Following a legal battle with its landlord, Just Above
Midtown/Corporation for Art and Television was evicted
from its space at 503 Broadway. Its staff continued pro-
gramming until 1989 under the names CATconcerts and
JAM Presents, producing several events at other venues
in New York.

MOST DEFINITELY NOT PROFILE LADIES is the third installation in a series
called "On The Spot". This exhibition series is designed to provide artists
with an opportunity to install site-specific work at JAM. "On The Spot" is
supported, in part, by funds from The New York State Council on the Arts, The
Edith C. Blum
Department of Cultural Affairs of the City of New York,
Foundation, Chase Manhattan Bank, Con Edison, Exxon Foundation and the artists
who rent JAM's facilities.
